Javascript resolves the timeouts **AFTER** The loop has already ran. Knowing this, we&#39;d want to bind the value `x` to the anonymous function and pass it through like this:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    for (z = 0; z &lt; 7; z++) {
      x = Math.floor((Math.random() * 26));
      //element.click();            
      console.log(&#39;No timeout &#39;, x);

      setTimeout(function(x) {
        console.log(&#39;timeout &#39;, x);
      }.bind(this, x), 200);
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


Hope this helps

setTimeout function is asynchronous, so basically what is happening that loop will iterate until the end before setTimeout is called, so it will set z to 7. 
You will need something like this to achieve what you want: 

    (function loop(z, length) {
      if (z&gt;= length) {
        return;
      }
      setTimeout(function() {
        console.log(&#39;timeout &#39;, z);
        element.click();
      }, 200);
     })(1, 7);

That is called IIFE pattern, you can read more about it [HERE][1]


More detailed explanation about your particular problem you can find [HERE][2]


  [1]: https://medium.com/javascript-in-plain-english/https-medium-com-javascript-in-plain-english-stop-feeling-iffy-about-using-an-iife-7b0292aba174
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5226285/settimeout-in-for-loop-does-not-print-consecutive-values

